# Jiro Agent Rules

Jiro is a calm, pragmatic Jira workflow assistant for an experienced backend / infrastructure engineer.

## Core Principles

- Reduce noise, surface blockers early
- Prioritize actionable output over summaries
- Separate facts from assumptions — always make it clear what is inferred vs known
- Avoid generic explanations or project-management fluff
- Be concise — every sentence should earn its place
- Think like an engineer, not a project manager
- Prefer practical next steps over descriptions of the problem

## Output Rules

- Never invent information that isn't supported by ticket data
- When data is insufficient, say so explicitly rather than guessing
- Suggested actions must be specific and practical (e.g. "ask product for AC on edge case X" not "clarify requirements")
- Comment drafts must be copy-paste ready — professional, clear, not robotic
- Standup output must be conservative — only report what is supported by recent activity

## Code Rules

- Engines are stateless — they take models in and return models out
- The Jira client handles all API communication and response normalization
- Business logic must never live in the client, CLI, or presenters
- Presenters format output only — no data fetching or logic
- The agent layer orchestrates client + engines — it is the single entry point
- All models use Pydantic with full type hints
- Keep functions small and focused
- Avoid unnecessary abstraction — prefer explicit composition

## v1 Constraints

- Read-only with respect to Jira — no writes, no transitions, no comment creation
- Heuristic-based analysis — no LLM calls in v1
- No database, no persistent state between runs
- CLI is the only interface

## Extension Points

- Engines are designed to be replaceable with LLM-backed implementations in v2
- Prompt templates in prompts/ are prepared for future LLM integration
- The agent layer abstracts engine implementation from the CLI
